         <abstract>
            <p>Italy's new government is likely soon to submit the legislative blueprint of its long-expected fiscal reforms to parliament. This major overhaul of the country's antiquated tax structure heralds a significant move in the direction of eliminating numerous indirect and nuisance taxes and of replacing them with a single, national income tax law, with tax credits mitigating the double taxation of distributed corporate earnings. A new "added value" sales tax will likewise tend to conform Italy's fiscal system to those in effect in other Common Market member countries. This reform may, in due course, profoundly affect Italy's securities markets and the evaluation of common stocks.</p>
          </abstract>
